{"id":10393,"category_id":6,"creator":"محرك","owner":"BBC","created_at":"17/05/2011","title":"محترفو النصب يستهدفون مستخدمي مواقع التواصل الإجتماعي","pictures":"//wscdn.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/assets/images/2011/05/16/110516154702_onlinefraud_624x351_bbc_nocredit.jpg","active":1,"views":659,"content":"Hello and welcome to BBC Xtra English!\r\nIn the past few years, social networking sites have experienced a huge rise in the number of members using them.\r\nThey offer their users an easy and entertaining way to maintain links with people they know and trust.\r\nBut this also makes social networking sites like Facebook an obvious target for scams involving impersonation.\r\nThe scale of the problem is highlighted in the latest six monthly security intelligence report from the computer software giant Microsoft.\r\nThe report took information from 600 million computer systems, and found that social networking provides a lucrative opportunity for fraudsters.\r\nIt claims there's been a 1,200 percent, or twelvefold, increase in so- called phishing attacks in just 12 months.\r\nThese phishing attacks take the form of apparently legitimate messages.\r\nThey convince the victim that they are from someone they know like friends or colleagues and then lure them into giving away information useful to criminals.\r\nThe report identifies two types of online scams.\r\nThe first are scams based on trickery that extract small bits of potentially useful personal data from large numbers of people.\r\nThe second are technologically sophisticated frauds - involving manipulation of software - aimed at stealing large sums from specifically targeted individuals.\r\nWhat type information do you share online? Write to us in English\r\nما هي المعلومات الشخصية التي تنشرها على مواقع التواصل الإجتماعي؟ اكتب لنا بالإنجليزية \r\nprogramme\r\nprogramme\r\n.لاستخدام هذا الملف لابد من تشغيل برنامج النصوص \"جافا\"، وأحدث الإصدارات من برنامج \"فلاش بلاير\"\r\nأحدث إصدارات برنامج \"فلاش بلاير\" متاحة هنا